                  "__cdata": "<p class=\"p_20 black\">Correct!</p><p>Correct answer is A : Rheumatoid arthritis<br/><p><strong style=\"color: rgb(25, 78, 130);\">Rheumatoid Arthritis&nbsp;</strong></p><p><strong style=\"color: rgb(147, 59, 3);\">Definition/Etiology </strong></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">RA is an autoimmune disorder predominantly of the joints but with many systemic manifestations of chronic inflammation. The cause is unknown </span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">although there is an association with specific HLA types. As with most autoimmune diseases, RA is more common in women. C\\</span></p><p><br></p><p><strong style=\"color: rgb(147, 59, 3);\">Diagnostic Tests</strong><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">•</span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Rheumatoid factor </span><strong style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">(RF) in 70% to 80%</strong><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">. RF is rather nonspecific and can be associated with many autoimmune and chronic infectious diseases. </span></p><p><strong style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Anti-cyclic citrullinated peptide (anti-CCP) </strong><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">is more than 80% sensitive and more than </span><strong style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">95% specific</strong><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">.</span></p><p><br></p><p><strong style=\"color: rgb(147, 59, 3);\">Treatment </strong></p><p><strong style=\"color: rgb(32, 100, 176);\">Disease Modifying Antirheumatic Drugs </strong></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Neither </span><strong style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">NSAIDs nor steroids stop RA from progressing</strong><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">. Any patient with erosive RA needs a disease modifying antirheumatic drug (DMARD) as part of </span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">initial therapy.&nbsp;</span></p><p><strong style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\"><em>Methotrexate </em></strong></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Methotrexate is the best initial DMARD. Adverse effects are: </span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Liver toxicity </span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Bone marrow suppression </span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Pulmonary toxicity&nbsp;</span></p><p>TiPS</p><ul><li><strong style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Morning stiffness </strong><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">of multiple small, inflamed joints is the key to the diagnosis.&nbsp;</span></li><li>DIP(DISTAL INTER PHALYNGEAL) JOINTED IS SPARED(UNINVOLVED) in RA,DIP_joint involved in Denerative Joint dz like OA</li><li><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Abnormal x-ray is not necessary to confirm diagnosis of RA.&nbsp;</span></li><li><strong style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">The most important issue in RA is stopping the progression of the disease. Any patient with erosive disease or x-ray abnormalities </strong></li></ul><p><strong style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">           needs at least methotrexate to slow disease progression.&nbsp;</strong></p><ul><li><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Steroids do not prevent the progression of RA.</span></li><li><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">The most common cause of death in RA is coronary artery disease.&nbsp;</span></li></ul>.</p>"
