            "__cdata": "<p class=\"p_20\">2. A 45-year-old woman presents to the rheumatology outpatient clinic with a three month history of stiff hands and wrists. She mentions that the pain is particularly bad first thing in the morning. On examination, the wrists, metacarpophalangeal joints and proximal interphalyngeal joints are swollen and warm. A diagnosis of rheumatoid arthritis is suspected. Which of the following investigations is most specific for confirming the diagnosis?</p>"
