                  "__cdata": "<p class=\"p_20 black\">Correct!</p><p>Correct answer is B : Osteoarthritis<br/><p><strong style=\"color: rgb(230, 0, 0);\">Osteoarthritis of the Knee</strong></p><p>Osteoarthritis, the most common joint abnormality, is associated with aging and increased use of a joint. </p><ul><li>The morning stiffness is &lt; 30 minutes in duration and there is crepitus on moving the joint. </li><li>OA affects the distal interphalangeal (DIP) joints (RA does not affect the DIPs). </li><li>Note the following:</li><li><span style=\"color: rgb(230, 0, 0);\">Heberden nodes: DIP osteophytes</span></li><li><span style=\"color: rgb(230, 0, 0);\">Bouchard nodes: PIP osteophytes</span></li></ul><p><strong style=\"color: rgb(230, 0, 0);\">Diagnostic Testing</strong></p><p><strong>The best initial test is </strong><strong style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">x-ray of the joint.</strong></p><p>All other inflammatory markers will be normal. Joint fluid will have a low</p><p>leukocyte count &lt; 2,000/mm3.</p><p><strong style=\"color: rgb(230, 0, 0);\">Treatment</strong></p><ol><li>Treatment is with <span style=\"color: rgb(230, 0, 0);\">acetaminophen</span><span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">. Chondroitin sulfate </span>is <span style=\"color: rgb(51, 51, 51);\">not </span>clearly useful to slow joint deterioration. Weight loss and exercise help.</li><li>If the question describes inadequate pain control with acetaminophen, then the answer is <span style=\"color: rgb(230, 0, 0);\">NSAIDs.</span> If NSAIDs do not adequately control the pain or there are contraindications to use (such as renal insufficiency or uncontrolled ulcer disease), then the answers are:</li><li>Duloxetine: SSRI/SNRI treats chronic musculoskeletal pain.</li></ol><p>\t\t\tTopical diclofenac: NSAID with less toxicity; use with renal insufficiency.</p><p>\t\t\tCapsaicin: Topical medicine, also for neuropathic pain</p><p>\t\t\tTramadol: Synthetic opioid that also inhibits reuptake of serotonin and norepinephrine</p><p><strong>When do you answer “knee replacement”? An elective knee replacement is</strong></p><p><strong>indicated when a patient develops severe symptoms</strong>, i.e., difficulty walking,inability to perform ADLs, or bone-on-bone disease seen on x-ray.</p>.</p>"
